Lots of new stuff learnt today around vnets and subnets in Azure.
Vnet is a resource in azure which needs a resource group under a subscription to be created.
Vnet is a physical boundary in Azure, which means 2 vm's in different Vnet can't talk untill we do VNET peering.
A very crucial practical knowledge around IP overlapping:
  Lab Details - HUBRG,AVDRG,DBRG,DCRG all under 1 subscription.
  1 dedicated VNET in HUBRG,1 dedicated in AVDRG and to verify possibility I tried same IP address space(HUBRG) with different subnet
  for DCRG but as expected, Azure threw a warning that similar address space is being used and it will not let you peer the vnet
  Reason being simple, currently you may have subnets which are not overlapping but what if you create subnet in future which have overlapping IP's
  To save Admins from that error, peering will not be available.

Learning 2 - 
 While creating vm's in different Resource groups, I didn't paid attention to the Vnet getting used.By default, Azure suggests you with 
default new VNET and if we don't select the VNET created for RG, then we will have 2 different VNETS with similar IP address space and subnets.
Now, if we peer the original VNET in RG, and try to ping, our request will fail.
REASON - the peering needs to be done between vnets which is attached to the VM's NIC.
Now to rectify my mistake, i had to delete vms and recreate it with selecting previously created VNET for the RG.
But just to workaround what i did is peered the VNET's attached to the VM that got created while creating VM.


Learning 3 - 
fought 2 hours trobleshooting why my ping is working when i denied the icmp packets on nsg.
I used every powershell cmdelt to see what is getting applying under the hood and all but nothing seem well, untill gemini told me on my 
response that ICMPv6 is different from icmp v4.I denied v6 and when we use ping it is V4 which was why my rule was not getting implemented.
commands i used were-
To find the NIC name and RG name - Get-agnetworkinterface.
To see effective security rules with deny ones- Get-AzEffectiveNetworkSecurityGroup -NetworkInterfaceName linux-vm-hub782 -ResourceGroupName hubrg |Select-Object -ExpandProperty EffectiveSecurityRules | Where-Object { $_.Access -eq "Deny" } | Format-Table Name, Priority, Access, Protocol

